{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17479979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17479979"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:35:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:35:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22626"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22626"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.87,0.06,0.04,0,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15579"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110951"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15579"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22626"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93074"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"882"},{"type":"tags","id":"1885"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"41918"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41919"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41920"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110951"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA newborn is delivered at 37 weeks gestation to a 41-year-old woman. The infant weighs 3.9 kg. The pregnancy was uncomplicated with normal antenatal screening. The mother has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, the infant appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The abdomen demonstrates the following abnormality (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://emedici.com/storage/images/25dc8a9e-2ab2-438d-ab2b-8c6083fc42b4.jpg\u0022\u003Eimage\u003C/a\u003E). The remainder of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Omphalocele","Gastroschisis","Umbilical hernia","Diaphragmatic hernia","Bladder exstrophy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows a newborn with a central abdominal wall defect at the umbilicus, with bowel contents visible through a translucent membrane. This appearance is characteristic of an omphalocele, a congenital defect where abdominal contents herniate through the umbilical ring but remain covered by peritoneum and amnion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOmphalocele\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct diagnosis. The key features are the central location at the umbilicus and the presence of a covering membrane over the herniated contents. Omphaloceles can contain bowel alone or may include liver and other organs. They are associated with chromosomal abnormalities and syndromes such as Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome in approximately 50% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastroschisis\u003C/strong\u003E is another abdominal wall defect but differs in several important ways. In gastroschisis, the defect is typically to the right of the umbilicus, and the herniated bowel is not covered by a membrane, appearing exposed and often matted together. The umbilical cord insertion is normal in gastroschisis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUmbilical hernia\u003C/strong\u003E presents as a bulge at the umbilicus but is covered by normal skin rather than a translucent membrane. It typically develops after birth and is reducible, unlike the fixed defect seen in this image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiaphragmatic hernia\u003C/strong\u003E involves herniation of abdominal contents into the thoracic cavity through a defect in the diaphragm. It would not present as a visible abdominal wall defect but rather with respiratory distress and a scaphoid abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBladder exstrophy\u003C/strong\u003E is a defect in the lower abdominal wall where the bladder is exposed. It appears as a red, mucosa-covered mass below the umbilicus, not at the umbilicus itself, and would not have the appearance shown in this image.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Omphalocele is a congenital abdominal wall defect where intestines and sometimes other organs protrude through the umbilicus, covered by a membrane.","Omphalocele differs from gastroschisis in that the herniated contents are covered by peritoneum and amnion, and it occurs at the umbilicus.","Omphalocele is associated with chromosomal abnormalities and syndromes including Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome in up to 50% of cases."],"references":["Borjas Mendoza PA, Mendez MD. Beckwith Wiedemann Syndrome. [Updated 2023 Feb 6]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK558993/","Shuman C, Beckwith JB, Weksberg R. Beckwith-Wiedemann Syndrome. 2000 Mar 3 [updated 2016 Aug 11]. In: Adam MP, Mirzaa GM, Pagon RA, Wallace SE, Bean LJH, Gripp KW, Amemiya A, editors. GeneReviews\u00ae [Internet]. Seattle (WA): University of Washington, Seattle; 1993\u20132023. PMID: 20301568.","Shuman C, Beckwith JB, Weksberg R. Beckwith-Wiedemann Syndrome. 2000 Mar 3 [Updated 2016 Aug 11]. In: Adam MP, Mirzaa GM, Pagon RA, et al., editors. GeneReviews\u00ae [Internet]. Seattle (WA): University of Washington, Seattle; 1993-2023. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK1394/","Munns CFJ, Batch JAHyperinsulinism and Beckwith-Wiedemann syndromeArchives of Disease in Childhood - Fetal and Neonatal Edition 2001;84:F67-F69.","Engstr\u00f6m, W., Lindham, S. \u0026 Schofield, P. Wiedemann-beckwith syndrome. Eur J Pediatr 147, 450\u2013457 (1988). https://doi.org/10.1007/BF00441965","Pettenati MJ, Haines JL, Higgins RR, et al. Wiedemann-Beckwith syndrome: presentation of clinical and cytogenetic data on 22 new cases and review of the literature. Hum Genet 1986; 74:143.","Engstr\u00f6m W, Lindham S, Schofield P. Wiedemann-Beckwith syndrome. Eur J Pediatr 1988; 147:450."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93074"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22626"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20198"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20198"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e90f5589-a6d4-4c23-ac82-baf8d4f0637f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e90f5589-a6d4-4c23-ac82-baf8d4f0637f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":705,"height":834}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93074"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-06T08:57:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-06T08:57:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15579"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110951"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":nul